# Dokkhota — Developer Setup (Sprint 1)

This file describes the minimal steps to run the project locally for Sprint 1 (backend + frontend) on Windows.

1) Prerequisites
- Node.js 18+ and npm
- MongoDB (local) OR a MongoDB Atlas cluster

2) Prepare backend env
- Copy the example: create `backend/.env` from `backend/.env.example` and fill values (especially `JWT_SECRET`).

3) Start or install MongoDB (local)
- If MongoDB is installed as a Windows service, start it:

  net start MongoDB

- Or run `mongod` manually from your MongoDB installation path.
- If you prefer Atlas, set `MONGO_URI` in `backend/.env` to your Atlas connection string.

4) Install dependencies and run
- Backend:

  cd backend
  npm install
  npm run dev

- Frontend:

  cd ../frontend
  npm install
  npm run dev

Notes & troubleshooting
- If backend shows SRV/DNS errors connecting to Atlas (ENOTFOUND _mongodb._tcp...), the app will automatically try the local MongoDB URI (`MONGO_LOCAL_URI`) as a fallback.
- The `frontend/package.json` `simple-peer` entry was pinned to a compatible version (`^9.11.1`). If you encounter issues, try clearing npm cache:

  npm cache clean --force
  npm install

- If `vite` is not recognized, ensure `npm install` completed successfully in `frontend` and run `npm run dev` from the `frontend` folder.

Creating an admin user (development)
- You can create an admin directly in MongoDB using a script or Mongo shell. Example (Mongo shell):

  use dokkhota
  db.users.insertOne({ name: 'Admin', email: 'admin@example.com', passwordHash: '<bcrypt-hash>', role: 'admin', creditBalance: 0, createdAt: new Date() })

Git commit message to use for these changes
- [FR-00] Fix dev environment: MongoDB fallback & frontend dependency pin
